Basic operations in R

The basic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division) in R are all done as you would expect.


Q1. Type the following lines in R and report the result of the mathematical expression.

12 * 3 - 10 / 2 + 16


Q2. Repeat the operation above, but this time add a pair of parentheses. What do you get now?

12 * (3 - 10 / 2) + 16

Note: In R, spaces are purely aesthetic. You get the same result whether you write 12 * 3 - 10 / 2 + 16 or 12*3-10/2+16, as you can verify for yourself.


Other common operations like exponentiation (raising a number to a power), square root, and the logarithm, are done using the symbol ^ and the functions sqrt(), log().

Q3. What is the result of the following expression:

2 ^ 3 - sqrt(16) + log(1)

Note: The caret symbol ^ raises a number to a power. Equivalently, you can use **. So for example 2 ^ 3 = 2 ** 3 = 8.


While we can work directly with numbers as above, it is much more convenient to assign values to variables and work with the variables instead. In R, the assignment operator is the = symbol.

Q4. Try the following code and report its result:

x = 12
y = 3
z = 10
w = 2
t = 16

x  * y - z / w + t


Note: You will find in some R texts assignments written using the symbol <- (meant to look like an arrow) rather than with the = sign. Those are interchangeable, so for example x <- 12 is fully equivalent to x = 12. In this course we will largely be using the equal sign rather than the arrow.


Q5. Just as the square root is the inverse function of squaring a number, the exponential function exp() is the inverse function of the logarithm. What is the result of exp(log(x))? Note: notice that the object name x was assigned the value of 12 in Q4. You can change that value to whatever you like. For example, you can write x = 5 and then try exp(log(x)), then change it to something else and try exp(log(x)) again.

Note: Sometimes you may want to add text to your R code as a note to yourself or another human reader which you do not intend for R to process. This is called a comment in programming lingo. You can add a comment by prefacing it with the hash symbol, as exemplified in the following code

x = 4

# x = 3. R will ignore this.

x

Functions

The text below about functions in R is reproduced with permission from Dr Gyorgi BarabÃ¡s at LinkÃ¶ping University, Sweden.

A function in R can be thought of as a vending machine with inputs (coins of various denominations, plus the buttons you press for a particular item) and outputs (Mars bars, Coke, and the like). Except the inputs are called arguments instead of coins, and the output is called the return value instead of Red Bull, as illustrated in this bit of sophisticated art:

                             --------------
            Argument 1 ----> |            |
            Argument 2 ----> |  FUNCTION  | ----> Return Value
            Argument 3 ----> |            |
                             --------------

When you ask a function to do something, youâ€™re calling the function. Youâ€™ve already called functions. Everything with a name followed by parentheses: (), possibly with things between the parentheses, is a function call: sqrt(), exp(), sample(), etc. When you type a function call at the R command line, R simply calls the function and displays the result on the next line. For example, when you execute sqrt(9), you are calling the built-in square root function. Its argument (input) is 9, and its return value is the square root of 9, or 3.

Here is a way to automate calculating the area of a circle with radius r:

circle_area = function(r) {
  area = r ^ 2 * pi
  return(area)
}

After executing the above lines, the computer now â€œknowsâ€ the function. Calling circle_area(3) will, for example, calculate the area of a circle with radius 3.

circle_area(r = 3)
## [1] 28.27433

One can define functions with more than one argument. For instance, here is a function that calculates the area of a rectangle with sides a and b:

rect_area = function(a, b) {
  area = a * b
  return(area)
}
rect_area(2, 3)
## [1] 6
rect_area(a = 2, b = 3)
## [1] 6

Notice how in either case we get the same result. Function arguments such as a and b in rect_area() can be called explicitly by name or implicitly by position.

Note: Any variables defined within a function (such as area above) are local to that function. So they are not visible from outside: even if area is defined within the function, one cannot access it from outside. You can test this by calling the object area on your console, and check out the error message you get.


Q6. Given a triangle with sides L1, L2, L3, its area is calculated via the formula Area = sqrt(p * (p - L1) * (p - L2) * (p - L3)), where p = (L1 + L2 + L3) / 2. Write an R function called tri_area that outputs the area of a triangle given its sides, and calculate the area of a triangle with sides L1 = 3, L2 = 4, L3 = 5.


Data structures

Vectors

So far we have been working with single numbers. However, when handling data we typically have a set of numbers to deal with. A vector is an example of a set of numbers. In R, we use the concatenate function c() to write vectors, as in the following example:

v = c(3, 5, -2, 0, 1)

The object v is now a vector with five elements. If you now run v in the console (i.e.Â type v and hit enter), R will print the contents of the vector, namely, 3 5 -2 0 1.

Note: If you donâ€™t know how many elements a vector contains, you can use the function length() to find out. For example, if you run length(v), R will print 5.


Q7. In R, we use square brackets [ ] to refer to specific elements of a vector. How would you look up the third element of vector v?

Note: We can also subset any number of elements of v. For example, the code v[c(4, 1)] will get you the fourth and the first element of v, in that order (try it!).


Q8. What does v[2:4] do? What do you deduce about the colon operator (:)? Test your hypothesis by running the command 1:10, and then the command 10:1.

Note: Another way to write a series of consecutive integers is with the function seq(). The command seq(a) will write all integers between 1 and a, and the command seq(a, b) will write all integers between a and b.


R has the very convenient functionality of extending operations on numbers to operations on vectors in an easy and intuitive way. So for example if we type 2 * v, we get

## [1]  6 10 -4  0  2

and if we type 10 ^ v, we get

## [1] 1e+03 1e+05 1e-02 1e+00 1e+01

Note: The numbers above are written in scientific notation, where the letter e stands for exponent (not to be confused with the mathematical constant e = 2.72 (Eulerâ€™s number), which is the base of the natural logarithm). So for example 1e+06 = 10 ^ 6 = 1,000,000 and 1e-02 = 1 / (10 ^ 2) = 0.01. Back in Q5 when you wrote exp(log(x)), the result is raising Eulerâ€™s number to the power log(x), which results in x.


If we perform one of the basic operations between two vectors of equal length, R will compute the operation element-by-element:

v1 = v
v2 = c(5, -1, -9, 2, 0)

v1 + v2
## [1]   8   4 -11   2   1
v1 / v2
## [1]  0.6000000 -5.0000000  0.2222222  0.0000000        Inf

Note: What happens when you try to add two vectors of different length, such as x1 = c(2, 3, 0), x2 = c(1, -1)? The answer is that R will perform the operation and issue a warning. Check it out! In general, watch out for unexpected results when you perform an operation between vectors of mismatching lengths.


We can also apply summarizing (i.e.Â statistical) functions to vectors, such as calculating the sum, product, mean, and variance of its elements:

sum(v2)
## [1] -3
prod(v1)
## [1] 0
mean(v1)
## [1] 1.4
var(v2)
## [1] 27.3


Q9. What is the output of mean(v1 + v2)? How does that compare with the output of sum(v1 + v2) / length(v1 + v2)?


Q10: You can sort or round the elements of a vector using functions sort() and round(). Try them out on the elements of mean(v1 + v2) by first assigning this quantity to a variable called my_vector and then applying these functions to my_vector.


The table below shows a list of commonly used functions in R that apply equally well to single numbers and vectors (after all, single numbers are vectors of length 1).

Note: One very helpful feature of R is that if you are not sure what a function does, you can look it up by typing ?function_name or help(function_name) in the console in R or RStudio â€“ or even by googling â€œfunction_name in Râ€. Try it out on the function sign by running ?sign. Oftentimes, the help page will provde usage examples in the bottom, which are typically the most helpful part.


As you can see, R works with vectors in much the same way it does with single numbers. Other important data structures in R include matrices, lists, and data frames.

Matrices

A matrix is essentially a two-dimensional vector. Here is one example:

my_matrix = matrix(c(2, 7, -2.2, 0, 1, 1, -19, 3.3, -1), nrow = 3, ncol = 3)

my_matrix
##      [,1] [,2]  [,3]
## [1,]  2.0    0 -19.0
## [2,]  7.0    1   3.3
## [3,] -2.2    1  -1.0

Just like with a vector, you can look up a specific element of a matrix via its coordinates (row and column):

my_matrix[3, 1]
## [1] -2.2

And you can even retrieve an entire row (or column) by simply leaving the corresponding coordinate blank:

my_matrix[2, ]
## [1] 7.0 1.0 3.3
my_matrix[, 3]
## [1] -19.0   3.3  -1.0

The same convenient element-by-element operations apply to matrices as they do to vectors. For example,

my_other_matrix = my_matrix - 5

my_other_matrix
##      [,1] [,2]  [,3]
## [1,] -3.0   -5 -24.0
## [2,]  2.0   -4  -1.7
## [3,] -7.2   -4  -6.0

We will make extensive use of matrices in the module of our course that examines growth in age-structured populations.


Q11. How would you create in R the following 3-by-2 matrix:

##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    4    1
## [2,]   -2    1
## [3,]    0    7


Lists

R can process non-numeric data as well. Other data types include character strings, logical values, and missing data. For example,

my_dogs_age = 3.5
my_dogs_name = 'Hobbes'
my_cats_name = NA
is_my_dog_a_puppy = my_dogs_age < 1
my_dogs_name
## [1] "Hobbes"
my_cats_name
## [1] NA
is_my_dog_a_puppy
## [1] FALSE

Note: Strings are always defined between single (â€™) or double (â€œ) quotation marks.

Note: NA means not applicable or not available.

NOte: Another symbol you may see R print sometimes is NaN. That means â€œnot a numberâ€, and results when you try to perform an illegal mathematical operation, such as division by zero. For example, try running 0/0 in the console.

Note: The last line in the code chunk above, is_my_dog_a_puppy = my_dogs_age < 1 may have confused you, because it is performing two operations at once: an assignment, and a logical test. The logical test operator < takes precedence over the assignment operator =. So R first tests whether my_dogs_age is less than 1, concludes that it is FALSE, and then assigns the value of FALSE to the name is_my_dog_a_puppy. The fact that the logical operator has precedence over the assignment operator is the reason why I didnâ€™t need to add parentheses. But when in doubt, it is good practice to add parenthesesâ€: the code line works equally and is easier for humans to parse if you write is_my_dog_a_puppy = (my_dogs_age < 1).

Note: Remember, the logical test for equality in R is ==, whereas the single = assigns values to object names. Sometimes when we want to check for equality between two objects A and B, we forget this and write A = B. This has a very different result than A == B.


Q12. Find out what the function str() does by applying it to each of the variables defined above. Report and interpret your results.


Notice, however, what happens when we try to concatenate the variables above into a single vector:

my_pet_info = c(my_dogs_age, my_dogs_name, my_cats_name, is_my_dog_a_puppy)

my_pet_info
## [1] "3.5"    "Hobbes" NA       "FALSE"
str(my_pet_info)
##  chr [1:4] "3.5" "Hobbes" NA "FALSE"

In trying to make a vector out of data of various types, we inadvertently created a vector where every element was turned into a character string.

The way to preserve the data structure is by creating a list:

my_pet_info = 
  list(
    my_dogs_age,
    my_dogs_name,
    my_cats_name,
    is_my_dog_a_puppy
  )

my_pet_info
## [[1]]
## [1] 3.5
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "Hobbes"
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] NA
## 
## [[4]]
## [1] FALSE
str(my_pet_info)
## List of 4
##  $ : num 3.5
##  $ : chr "Hobbes"
##  $ : logi NA
##  $ : logi FALSE

Note: As with spaces, line breaks are purely aesthetic in R code.

We can retrieve an element of a list via double square brackets. For example,

my_pet_info[[2]]
## [1] "Hobbes"

Lists (and also vectors) can have name attributes:

my_dog_info = 
  list(
    age = my_dogs_age,
    name = my_dogs_name,
    puppy = is_my_dog_a_puppy
  )

We can retrieve elements from named lists by name via a $ sign:

my_dog_info$name
## [1] "Hobbes"

Tidyverse

Throughout the course we will use the suite of R packages called tidyverse, designed to standardize and facilitate the processing and analysis of data frames in R.

You have already installed the tidyverse suite, and you can load it by typing library(tidyverse). In fact, the first thing to do at the beginning of each lab section in the course will be to run the code lines at the top of the write-up which load all of the packages (a.k.a. libraries) that will be used in that lab.

Coding in the tidyverse is analogous to writing â€œsentencesâ€ with â€œnounsâ€ (data structures such as vectors and data frames) and â€œverbsâ€ (operations on data structures, i.e.Â functions which receive as input a data structure). Once you get the hang of this grammar, you may find it very intuitive to manipulate data in R.

We connect the nouns and verbs using the pipe symbol |> (or equivalently the older pipe symbol %>%). Here is an example of a short sentence that turns the row names of mtcars into a column called model using the verb rownames_to_column():

car_dataframe = 
  mtcars |>
  rownames_to_column(var = 'model')

It is useful to store the results of our work in an object which we can later call at any time, as we did above. This is easily done using the assignment symbol = on top of the sentence. Q16. By piping the verb arrange(), write code that prints the characters tibble with rows arranged by the year the character was created. (Hint: just put the name of the column inside the verb)


One of the great advantages of the tidyverse grammar is that we donâ€™t need to apply one verb at a time. The code chunk below starts with the object mtcars, then pipes five verbs to it one at a time, then assigns the resulting object the name new_car_tibble:

new_car_tibble = 
  mtcars |>
  rownames_to_column(var = 'model') |>
  as_tibble() |>
  mutate(kml = mpg * 0.43) |>
  select(model, kml, cyl) |>
  filter(cyl == 4, kml > 10) |>
  arrange(kml)

Letâ€™s unpack the code chunk above.

  • We assign the name new_car_tibble to an object created as follows:
  • First, take the built-in data frame mtcars,
  • next, convert its row names to a new column named model,
  • then, convert the whole object into a tibble,
  • then, create a new column named kml (kilometers per liter) by multiplying mpg by 0.43 (as 1 mile per gallon = 0.43 kilometers per liter),
  • then, select only the columns model, kml, and cyl (number of cylinders),
  • then, we filter the tibble to keep only the cars with 4 cylinders and fuel efficiency \(>\) 10 km/liter,
  • finally, arrange the cars by fuel efficiency.

We can inspect the resulting tibble by calling it:

## 6 Fiat 128        13.9     4
## 7 Toyota Corolla  14.6     4


As you can see, a sentence in tidyverse can have as many pipes as we want. In fact, the idea behind naming the symbol |> pipe is that you have information flowing down a pipeline. The piping structure allows R to apply an indefinite number of verbs on a data structure in order, and makes it easy to follow what is being done in each code line.

Note: Notice how the verb mutate() can be used to create new columns from scratch, as we did in the characters tibble, or based on existing ones, as we just did above.

Note: We can impose any number of filters at once on a single line, as we just did above when filtering at the same time for a specified number of cylinders and minimum fuel efficiency.

Reading data

So far we have been working with a built-in data set, mtcars. However, in most cases of interest we will want to read data from an external source, such as an online data repository. R has a number of functions to read external data. You will not need to know how to use those functions, as the code for reading the data set in question will always be provided to you in this course.

The following is one such example of importing a data set from an external source. In this case the external source is my BIO 356 GitHub page, and the data set shows estimates of the eastern North Pacific population of gray whales based on whale sightings off the coast of California between 1968 and 2002.

Figure: Gray whale (Eschrichtius robustus) breaching in San Diego, CA. Photo credit: lajolla.com

github_address = 'https://github.com/rafaeldandrea/BIO-356/blob/master/gray_whales.xlsx?raw=true'

whale_dataset = 
  rio::import(github_address, range = 'B6:G28') |> 
  as_tibble()

  • The first line of code creates a string object called github_address, containing the URL where the data set is stored.

  • I then create an object called whale_dataset which first imports the data set using that address via the function (verb) import() from R package â€œrioâ€ (which you already installed on your computer along with all other required packages for the course, and loaded it above when you copy/pasted all libraries from this weekâ€™s write-up).

  • Finally, I convert the data set to a tibble so we can easily visualize the data.

Note: The double-colon symbol :: tells R explicitly where to look for a function. This is useful in cases where more than one R package contain functions with the same name, or when you are not sure whether you already loaded the R package in question. The usage is always package_name::function_name.

Plotting

In addition to reading and manipulating data, we often want to visualize our data using plots. The tidyverse environment in R has a whole grammar for making plots, into which we will dip our toes here. Again, you are not required to master this so-called grammar of graphics, as the code for plotting things will always be provided to you. Rather, you will often be asked to tweak provided code to modify a given plot, so what you want is to be able to understand the gist of provided code.

Letâ€™s use the whale data set above to make some plots.

plot_whales = 
  whale_dataset |> 
  ggplot(aes(End_dates, New_abundance)) + 
  geom_point()

plot_whales

The scatter plot above shows abundance estimates on the y-axis and dates on the x-axis. We follow the same type of noun-and-verbs pipeline as we were doing above when manipulating tibbles. We start with the whale_dataset object, then pipe in the verb ggplot(), which tells R that everything that will follow are verbs that apply to graphic objects. Indeed, after the verb ggplot() we pipe in the verb geom_point(), which tells R to make a plot where the datapoints are represented by dots.

You will notice that inside the verb ggplot() we have aes(End_dates, New_abundance). This is what tells R what to plot on the x-axis (i.e.Â the horizontal axis) and what to plot on the y-axis (i.e.Â the vertical axis). The syntax here is always ggplot(aes(column_name_1, column_name_2)), where column_name_1 will be plotted on the x-axis and column_name_2 on the y-axis. Then once we pipe in the verb geom_point(), R already knows what is going on each axis and simply draws the points. The whole thing is then stored in the object plot_whales, and the plot is actually drawn on your screen once you call the object.

Note: Sadly, the developers of this system decided to use the addition symbol + to pipe together plot-oriented verbs rather than the |> pipe symbol used for tibbles. It would have been nice if we could just stick to a single unified pipe symbol for all objects in R, but you canâ€™t have everything.

What if we wanted to connect the dots? R has the verb geom_line() for that. You can just pipe it into the plot_whales object, as follows:

plot_whales + 
  geom_line()

Q19. What do we get if instead of creating the object plot_whales without the connecting lines and then piping in geom_line() as we just did above, we define the object with the geom_line() verb piped into it directly? Show R code that does this, then make your plot.


This is the basic tidyverse way of constructing plots from data sets in R. We can do much more by just piping in more verbs, and by modifying the arguments inside the verbs from their default values. For example,

plot_whales = 
  whale_dataset |> 
  ggplot(aes(End_dates, New_abundance)) + 
  geom_line(color = 'red') +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(
    x = 'Year',
    y = 'Abundance'
  ) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  ggtitle('Whale population estimates')

plot_whales

In the code above, after adding geom_point() which draws the dots and geom_line() which draws the connecting line, we added labs(), which lets us change the labels on the axes, theme() which lets us change many different aspects of the plot â€“ here, the overall shape of the plot, which I made square by setting aspect.ratio = 1 â€“ and then added ggtitle(), which prints a name for the plot on top.

Notice that I changed the color of the connecting line to red by setting the argument color = "red" inside geom_line(), and the size of the dots by setting the argument size = 2 in geom_point(), and I changed the order of geom_line() and geom_point() which puts the dots in front of the line since they are drawn after the line. The latter illustrates the flexibility of this piping system with regards to the order of the verbs.

What if we want to add error bars? Not a problem:

plot_whales = 
  whale_dataset |> 
  ggplot(aes(End_dates, New_abundance)) + 
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(
      x = End_dates, 
      ymin = New_abundance + New_SE, 
      ymax = New_abundance - New_SE
    ),
    color = 'blue'
  ) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    x = 'Year',
    y = 'Abundance'
  ) +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  ggtitle('Whale population estimates')

plot_whales

In the plot above we used the column New_SE in the data set to draw the error bars. Notice how the verb geom_errorbar() needs an argument aes() similar to the one in ggplot(), and inside that argument we provide information on what should go on the x-axis (End_dates), and what should be the minimum and maximum values on the y-axis. I also removed the connecting line so the plot doesnâ€™t get too busy.

Control flow

In ecology, we often have data sets that we want to use to answer ecological questions such as â€œIs the population of eastern North Pacific gray whales increasing?â€. As we have seen so far, R is excellent at reading, wrangling, and visualizing data such that we can easily get our answers to questions like these.

However, a lot of times ecologists want to make predictions about what has not yet been seen. What are the chances that gray whales will go extinct within 50 years, given what we know about their population over the past 30 years? How much of a rise in global temperatures should we expect within the next 20 years? What is the expected human population in 100 years? To answer questions like these, ecologists may use simulated data (since we canâ€™t observe the future!), which in turn is obtained using models and computers.

While so far we have been emphasizing R as a tool of statistical analysis, next we will look at its usefulness as a tool for generating simulated data.

Computers are famous for speed and automation. In other words, they can repeateadly perform many calculations fast. In any computing language, this is ultimately done via control flow structures such as conditional statements and for-loops. Here we will look at how to use them in R.


Conditional statements

Conditional statements are also called if-statements, and they rely on logical tests.

Hereâ€™s a simple logical test in R

2 > 3
## [1] FALSE

We get a result of FALSE, which is a logical object. In R, the function if() receives as an argument a logical object and returns an action that the user specifies. This is what an if-statement is. Hereâ€™s an example if-statement in R:

if(2 > 3){
  print('Two is greater than three')
}

When you enter the code above, nothing happens because R ignores what is inside the curly brackets {} since the argument of the if() function was FALSE.

We can also tell R what to do in case the logical test returns FALSE:

if(2 > 3){
  print('Two is greater than three')
} else { 
  print('Two is NOT greater than three')
}
## [1] "Two is NOT greater than three"

In this piece of (hopefully) simple and intuitive code, R tests whether 2 > 3, concludes that this is FALSE, and then skips what is inside the curly brackets (since the argument of if() was FALSE), then finds an else statement, which tells it what to do in case the first test was FALSE. This is the R syntax for if-else expressions.

We can refine the code some more:

if(2 > 3){
  print('Two is greater than three')
} else if(2 == 3){ 
  print('Two is equal to three')
} else {
  print('Two is less than three')
}
## [1] "Two is less than three"

The code above introduces the else if structure, which allows you to ask about more than two possible options (2 can be greater than, equal to, or less than 3).

Note: Note that when checking whether 2 is equal to three, we use the double == sign, not the single = sign. The difference is that when doubled, the equal signs represent a logical test (we are checking if two things are equal), while the single equal sign is the assignment symbol (we are assigning a value to an object). So for example the code x = 2 tells R to assign the value 2 to an object called x (if x already existed and had a different value, that will now be overwritten to 2), whereas the code x == 2 tests whether it is true that the value assigned to object x is 2 (if x had not been previously defined in the code, youâ€™ll get the expected error message â€œobject â€˜xâ€™ not foundâ€).


Q21. Replace the logical symbol == in the code above with the assignment symbol = and show the error message that you get. (To coerce RStudio to knit despite the error, add error = TRUE inside the heading of your code chunk â€“ i.e make your code chunk heading read {r error = TRUE})

Note: In addition to > and ==, the other relational logical operators in R are of course <, <= (less than or equal to), >=, and != (NOT equal to).


For-loops

A lot of times we want R to perform many operations at once. One way to do that is with for-loops. See if you can make sense of the code below and its outcome:

for(i in 1:5){
  print(i)
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

Hereâ€™s code combining a for loop and an if statement:

for(i in 1:5){
  if(i != 3){
    print(i)
  }
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

The code above loops the object i through the integers 1 to 5 in turn, each time checking whether it is NOT equal to three, in which case it prints the value of i.


Q22. The R operator for the remainder of a division by an integer is %% (double percent sign). For instance, 11 %% 4 is equal to 3, since 11 = 2 * 4 + 3. Write R code that sweeps an object i from 1 to 5 and prints it only if the object is an odd number. (Hint: You can define even and odd numbers in terms of the remainder of dividing by 2)


A similar structure to a for-loop in R is a while-loop. See if you can figure out what the code below does:

i = 0
while(i < 5){
  i = i + 1
  if(i != 3){
    print(i)
  }
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 4
## [1] 5

Notice two differences from the for-loop: you need to specify the initial value of the argument, and you need to update the argument inside the while-loop. Other than that, the code is identical to the for-loop above.

The reason we are talking about conditional statements and for-loops in this lab is that they are instrumental for simulating ecological models, whose simulated data we can then use to answer ecological questions.

For example, one very simple model of population growth in ecology (which we will examine in detail in the next module) is the following expression

\[ N_{t+1} = \lambda N_t \]

where \(N_t\) is the population size at time \(t\) and \(\lambda\) is called the growth rate. The expression is saying that every time unit (say, every year), the population grows by a multiplicative factor \(\lambda\).

We can use this data to simulate what happens to this population over time. Suppose \(\lambda = 1.1\) and \(N = 50\) at year 0. The following R code will compute the population size at all subsequent years for 20 years.

lambda = 1.1
N = 50
N_vector = N
for(year in 1:20){
  N = round(lambda * N)
  N_vector = c(N_vector, N)
}

N_vector
##  [1]  50  55  61  67  74  81  89  98 108 119 131 144 158 174 191 210 231 254 279
## [20] 307 338

The lines above the for loop specify the parameter value and initial abundance, then the new abundances are calculated for each year in turn. The object N_vector stores the abundance values for each year (notice how it is updated in every iteration of the for loop being concatenating to the most recent abundance value).

We can more easily understand what these simulated data are showing us by plotting the results. Letâ€™s do that next:

data = 
  tibble(
    year = 0:20,
    abundance = N_vector
  )

plot = 
  data |>
  ggplot(aes(year, abundance)) +
  geom_line(color = 'grey') +
  geom_point()

plot

As we can see, the model predicts that the population will grow in an accelerated fashion every year. We will have much more to say about population growth in the next few weeks.


Q23. Modify the code above to see what happens to the population when we change the growth rate to \(\lambda = 0.9\). Make a plot and show it in your answer.


This simple exercise illustrates how we can use R to study ecological questions. In the upcoming modules of the class, our focus will shift towards the ecological topics, and R will be our tool for exploring those topics.


Random variables

Many processes in nature are best described as stochastic, meaning they contain an element of randomness. A textbook example of a stochastic process is a coin toss. Other examples in science include radiation, cancer development, and yes, ecological processes.


Figure: Diagramatic representation of a stochastic model of tumor development, from Fanali et al.Â 2014


To simulate stochastic processes, all computer languages must have ways of generating random numbers. R is no exception. In R, you can generate a random number between 0 and 1 using the function runif()

runif(1)
## [1] 0.5918192

In general, you can generate n random numbers between a and b by specifying the parameters of the function runif:

runif(n = 10, min = -5, max = 6)
##  [1] -3.4469352 -4.0992180 -4.1197441 -0.5891056 -3.1801808  0.9600169
##  [7]  4.9691437  3.6262118 -1.9322390  4.4679605

Notice that if you repeat the experiment, you wonâ€™t obtain the same random numbers:

runif(n = 10, min = -5, max = 6)
##  [1] -0.3251004  4.2651135 -3.4903131  2.5849608  1.5720195  4.1193440
##  [7]  2.5126577 -4.6395313  1.9221176 -4.2509683

However, it is also useful for the purposes of reproducible research to control the generation of random numbers. In other words, we might want our random numbers to be random but also replicable. To do that, we can use a function called set.seed(). Watch this:

set.seed(0)
runif(n = 10, min = -5, max = 6)
##  [1]  4.8636692 -2.0794047 -0.9066371  1.3013870  4.9902857 -2.7814988
##  [7]  4.8822865  5.3914280  2.2687757  1.9202545
set.seed(0)
runif(n = 10, min = -5, max = 6)
##  [1]  4.8636692 -2.0794047 -0.9066371  1.3013870  4.9902857 -2.7814988
##  [7]  4.8822865  5.3914280  2.2687757  1.9202545

Once you set the â€œseedâ€, every random number generated afterwards will be determined. Therefore, you and I can get the same random numbers in our respective computers by setting the seed at the top of our R code.

Note: If you are wondering how random numbers can be determined in any way, you are on to something! Truly random numbers canâ€™t be reproducible by definition. Computer languages like R use so-called pseudorandom numbers. If you are curious, check out this accessible YouTube video explaining pseudorandom numbers and how computers generate them. But for the purposes of this course, all you need to know is that we can control the production of our random numbers by calling the function set.seed() with a specified value to its argument (I used 0 in the example above but we could have used any number).


R can also pick random numbers from a specified set using function sample():

sample(c(1, 0, -3, 7, 5), size = 10, replace = TRUE)
##  [1]  0 -3 -3  1  5  5  0  0  1  5

R can also use specific probability distributions to generate random numbers. For example, the function rnorm() draws random numbers following a normal distribution:

set.seed(1)

random_numbers = rnorm(n = 1000, mean = 0, sd = 1)

random_data = 
  tibble(
    x = random_numbers
  )

plot_data = 
  random_data |>
  ggplot(aes(x)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = 'darkred') +
  xlim(c(-5, 5))

plot_data

The code above first sets the seed to 1, then draws 1000 random numbers from a normal distribution, then puts them in a tibble, and finally draws a histogram with 30 bins.

Note: The verb xlim piped into plot_data simply fixes the range of plotted values in the figure (by default R will use a range that contains the whole data without leaving unnecessary white space).

As you may have guessed, the arguments mean and sd in rnorm() control the mean and standard deviation across the random numbers we drew. The histogram above confirms that indeed our random numbers are centered around 0.
